NBA ‘GOATS’ statistical analysis

Matt JB Corrado

May 18, 2020

The Best Fan-Favorite (Meme) NBA Player

1. Introduction

Everyone who is a fan of the NBA has heard time and time again the debate over who is truly the greatest to play the game. This debate just becomes so repetitive over time that I wanted to shine a new light on some of the players that do not get the statistical analysis they deserve. I searched the web and after checking countless sites, I chose the 5 fan-favorite role players in NBA history. The five players include Lance Stephenson (LeBron’s personal ear blower, video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cz3wvCNnF98), Alex Caruso (the baby GOAT himself, video: https://youtu.be/B_qEGsBHVWg?t=4), JaVale McGee (the Shaqtin’ A Fool GOAT, video: https://youtu.be/YSeszFGQ_v0?t=10), Brian Scalabrine (The White Mamba, video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AnXQsJ8ung8), and Boban Marjanović (Bobi The Friendly Giant [John Wick 3 Star], video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CZqyEHErXMc, also John Wick scene: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZSbLUv7WSXE). The way I will find out who is the best player of these five is by using their player stats that I scrapped from basketball-reference.com to compare their major statistical categories: points per game, rebounds per game, assists per game, steals per game, blocks per game, turnovers per game, fouls per game. After comparing their stats directly, I will adjust them to be per 36 minutes (league average for a starter) and compare their efficiency.

a. Points per Game

ppg_table <- tibble(name = "Alex Caruso", ppg = ac_career[1,"PTS"]/ac_career[1,"G"])
ppg_table <- ppg_table %>% add_row(name = "Boban Marjavonić", ppg = bm_career[1,"PTS"]/bm_career[1,"G"])
ppg_table <- ppg_table %>% add_row(name = "JaVale McGee", ppg = jm_career[1,"PTS"]/jm_career[1,"G"])
ppg_table <- ppg_table %>% add_row(name = "Brian Scalabrine", ppg = bs_career[1,"PTS"]/bs_career[1,"G"])
ppg_table <- ppg_table %>% add_row(name = "Lance Stephenson", ppg = ls_career[1,"PTS"]/ls_career[1,"G"])
ggplot(ppg_table, aes(x=name,y = ppg, color = name)) + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "white")

As clearly shown by the graph, Lance is the top scorer with 8.57 ppg, followed by JaVale (7.91), Boban (6.17), Alex (5.66), and Brian (3.07) (in that order). 3. Player Efficiency

Player efficiency will be broken down into six different sections: 2-point field goal percentage, 3-point field goal percentage, free throw percentage, overall field goal percentage, effective field goal percentage (which takes in account that a three point is worth more than a two pointer), and a player efficiency rating (explained later).

a. 2-Point field goal percentage

tpfgp_table <- tibble(name = "Alex Caruso", tpfgp = ac_eff[1,"2P%"])
tpfgp_table <- tpfgp_table %>% add_row(name = "Boban Marjavonić", tpfgp = bm_eff[1,"2P%"])
tpfgp_table <- tpfgp_table %>% add_row(name = "JaVale McGee", tpfgp = jm_eff[1,"2P%"])
tpfgp_table <- tpfgp_table %>% add_row(name = "Brian Scalabrine", tpfgp = bs_eff[1,"2P%"])
tpfgp_table <- tpfgp_table %>% add_row(name = "Lance Stephenson", tpfgp = ls_eff[1,"2P%"])
ggplot(tpfgp_table, aes(x=name,y = tpfgp, color = name)) + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "white")

Based on the graph, Boban has the highest 2-point field goal percentage over his career (58.5%), followed by JaVale (57.8%), Lance (49.4%), Alex (46.4%), and Brian (41.5%). I will assign points to the player to use later as a way to find out who is the best (top: 4 points, second: 3 points, third: 2 points, fourth: 1 point, and last: 0 points), since the players play different positions and are most likely to take certain shot types over other types.

f. Custom Player Efficiency Rating

The way I constructed my PER was by taking the effective field goal percentage * points per minutes played + rebounds per minutes played + assists per minutes played.

per_table <- tibble(name = "Alex Caruso", per = (ac_eff[1,"eFG%"]*(ac_career[1,"PTS"]/ac_career[1,"MP"]))+(ac_career[1,"TRB"]/ac_career[1,"MP"])+(ac_career[1,"AST"]/ac_career[1,"MP"]))
per_table <- per_table %>% add_row(name = "Boban Marjavonić", per = (bm_eff[1,"eFG%"]*(bm_career[1,"PTS"]/bm_career[1,"MP"]))+(bm_career[1,"TRB"]/bm_career[1,"MP"])+(bm_career[1,"AST"]/bm_career[1,"MP"]))
per_table <- per_table %>% add_row(name = "JaVale McGee", per = (jm_eff[1,"eFG%"]*(jm_career[1,"PTS"]/jm_career[1,"MP"]))+(jm_career[1,"TRB"]/jm_career[1,"MP"])+(jm_career[1,"AST"]/jm_career[1,"MP"]))
per_table <- per_table %>% add_row(name = "Brian Scalabrine", per = (bs_eff[1,"eFG%"]*(bs_career[1,"PTS"]/bs_career[1,"MP"]))+(bs_career[1,"TRB"]/bs_career[1,"MP"])+(bs_career[1,"AST"]/bs_career[1,"MP"]))
per_table <- per_table %>% add_row(name = "Lance Stephenson", per = (ls_eff[1,"eFG%"]*(ls_career[1,"PTS"]/ls_career[1,"MP"]))+(ls_career[1,"TRB"]/ls_career[1,"MP"])+(ls_career[1,"AST"]/ls_career[1,"MP"]))
ggplot(per_table, aes(x=name, y = per, color = name)) + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1)) + geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "white")
